Actually on type 1 engines using the stock pulley setup with the little 
disks I have had more than one loose pulley happen.  One I was right at 
the engine and heard the funny metal knock and it still took a while to 
find it.  the pulley was not very loose at all and making a knocking 
noise.
jimt
On Thursday, August 8, 2002, at 09:50 , John Rogers wrote:
> . The inner half of the generator pulley had
> literally broken into pieces although the hub was still on the shaft. 
> The
> source of blue smoke had been the fan belt being chewed before it was
> flipped.. With the installation of a new pulley the mysterious knocking
> disappeared. Presumably it had been caused by an out of round, out of
> balance failing pulley.
> Let me hasten to add that I suspect what happened to me was a very rare
> occurrence and not likely to be the source of your knocking.
> The lesson, however, is to consider everything, not just the usual 
> suspects.
